    {
        "content": "<p>It's from this book:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://assets.cambridge.org/97805212/83618/excerpt/9780521283618_excerpt.pdf\">https://assets.cambridge.org/97805212/83618/excerpt/9780521283618_excerpt.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 536985835,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756649433
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay!  They much be talking about functions from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span>.   The real line is a somewhat unusual entity in that it's typically defined as a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/complete%20ordered%20field\">[[complete ordered field]]</a>, and when we give it all that structure, it's not only uniquely characterized up to isomorphisms - it has <em>no endomorphisms except the identity</em>.  In hand-wavy terms, it's completely rigid. </p>\n<p>So we have to <em>remove</em> structure from that complete ordered field to make it more floppy - to give it more endomorphisms.</p>\n<p>This is different from complex numbers, where you've always got complex conjugation until you say which number is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6595em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span></span></span></span> and which is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-i</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7429em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span></span></span></span>.   It's dramatically different from the field of algebraic numbers, which is cursed with a plague of automorphisms.</p>",
        "id": 536988064,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1756651966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm getting the sense from your answer, that my understanding for how functions on the real line are related won't generalize to how functions defined on other spaces work.</p>\n<p>So if I look at the homset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of functions between real numbers, there are no nontrivial isomorphisms relating this to some other homset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(X, Y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. And therefore when understanding real functions with special properties, it amounts to choosing subsets of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>When nontrivial automorphisms enter the picture this is no longer true, now we start having categorical flavored relationships operating at a higher level than just the subsets.</p>\n<p>Is this a good way to understand the significance of your examples?</p>",
        "id": 536990074,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756654188
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>So if I look at the homset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathbb{R}, \\mathbb{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of functions between real numbers, there are no nontrivial isomorphisms relating this to some other homset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(X, Y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Huh, what?  That barely makes sense.   But more importantly, it sounds false.</p>\n<p>In the category of sets and functions there are <em>tons</em> of automorphisms of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span>: any bijective map sending real numbers to real numbers will do.   There are even <em>more</em> isomorphisms between the set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathbb{R}, \\mathbb{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> and certain other homsets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>Y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(X, Y)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.   If I count correctly, there can be exactly</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℵ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></msup></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 2^{2^{\\aleph_0}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0119em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.0119em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.927em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">ℵ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3448em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.1em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2996em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> </p>\n<p>of them.</p>\n<p>What I said is that usually <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> is given as a complete ordered field.   Then people prove that given any two complete ordered fields, there's exactly one morphism between them.   </p>\n<p>So at this point, at its birth, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> is not a mere set.  It's a complete ordered field.   It's been given so much structure that it has no nontrivial automorphisms - or even endomorphisms.     We then spend a lot of time 'stripping off' or 'forgetting' structure: hitting it with functors that turn it into a topological space, or a manifold, or an ordered set, or whatever.  This makes it more flexible.</p>",
        "id": 536996494,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1756661674
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, you're touching on something I'm deeply confused about, which is good. I'll do my best to try to ask questions that give some sense of where my head is.</p>\n<p>I wanted to define operations on the complete ordered field, but I can't because it has so much structure that in order to preserve it I'm stuck with the identity function. So like you said we forget structure to give us room to do more things.</p>\n<p>But often it seems like when I'm working with the complete ordered field <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span>, I forget everything, but keep the forgotten structure in the back of my mind, and add it back when I can.</p>\n<p>So given functions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f, g : \\mathcal{R} \\rightarrow \\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span>, with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(x) = x^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> I know it's differentiable, but with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">g(x) = x^3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">g</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> It's even monotonic! If I have an absolute value function it's merely continuous. I'm choosing functions, and noting later the structure that hasn't been forgotten. But they are all written as if they're functions from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{R} \\rightarrow \\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span>, arrows in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>. They all are living together in an analysis textbook, but \"actually\" live in different categories.</p>\n<p>I have a feeling or intuition that I'm confused, because if I'm working in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, like you said, at any time I could compose whatever composite function I'm building with an arbitrary function thereby completely scrambling up what I was doing.</p>\n<p>But, thinking I'm working in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, is how I've been pretending to coordinate functions from different categories. I imagine what their graphs look like, decide what properties I think they have, and move forward from there.</p>\n<p>How is this coordination actually supposed work?</p>",
        "id": 537000527,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756665823
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Some other aspect that's confused me, that I see connected with this somehow. I can visualize any function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : \\mathcal{R} \\rightarrow \\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span> by using the metric on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span>, but most of the functions don't preserve distance, so in what sense is it meaningful to graph these functions?</p>",
        "id": 537000773,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756666091
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Math rarely uses just one category at a time.  Note that the very <em>definition</em> of a field starts by saying \"it's a set with...\" a bunch of operations that are functions between sets.  So the category of fields, like many categories,  is defined as a category with af forgetful functor to Set, and you can't do anything (or least not much) without using that.</p>\n<p>Most mathematicians work promiscuously among many categories and are wise enough to not pay too attention to this.  If you do, you could easily become like millipede who tries to keep track of its legs and gets paralyzed!  But you can figure it out if necessary.</p>",
        "id": 537001246,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1756666611
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe we could focus on a characteristic or simple example so I can get a feeling for how this works?</p>\n<p>Like what were you trying to illustrate by pointing out the category of complete ordered fields had only one object up to unique isomorphism, whereas other algebraic categories have several? It seems they all use forgetful functors into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> in an analogous way. In what way are the automorphisms of the field of algebraic numbers a plague?</p>\n<p>I'd think more automorphisms would be useful exactly because it makes the object less rigid, but instead it seems that's what the forgetful functors are for.</p>",
        "id": 537005273,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756670574
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I'm trying to fix my confusion that caused the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> mistake, I'm failing to juggle the categories now that I know they're there <span aria-label=\"joy\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f602\" role=\"img\" title=\"joy\">:joy:</span>)</p>",
        "id": 537009596,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756675685
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277352\">Alex Kreitzberg</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Contextualizing.20how.20continuity.20is.20taught.20with.20categories/near/537005273\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Like what were you trying to illustrate by pointing out the category of complete ordered fields had only one object up to unique isomorphism, whereas other algebraic categories have several?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I was mainly saying that since all the morphisms in the category of complete ordered field are isomorphisms, and there's a unique isomorphism between any two complete ordered fieldd, you're <em>doomed</em> if you're hoping for any interesting functions from the real numbers to themselves to be morphisms in the category of complete ordered fields.  So despite how we say \"the real numbers are defined to be a complete ordered field\", we need to go down to some other category (like Set, or Top, etc.) to find interesting functions from the real numbers to themselves.</p>\n<p>On the other hand, this rigidity means that we can call any complete algebraic field \"the\" real numbers, and never get in trouble: any one of <em>your</em> real numbers corresponds to a unique one of mine.   </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In what way are the automorphisms of the field of algebraic numbers a plague?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I was just joking, but it's well-known that the group of automorphisms of the field of algebraic numbers is huge and unknowable, and there's an apocryphal story that thinking about it has driven mathematicians mad.   I've never heard of any evidence for that story.  Grothendieck <em>did</em> work on that group (cf. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grothendieck%E2%80%93Teichm%C3%BCller_group\">Grothendieck-Teichmuller theory</a>) and he <em>did</em> sort of go mad, but probably not because of trying to understand that group.</p>",
        "id": 537011264,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1756677660
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, if I imagine the category of complete ordered fields, it's just a point right? And then we have forgetful functors from that point to other categories, that all also have faithful forgetful functors into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>?</p>\n<p>So do we have a sort of lattice of forgetful functors? Is this related to the subset picture I shared at the beginning?</p>",
        "id": 537011903,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756678173
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The point would pick out an object in each of these categories, and if all the functors were faithful, you could float up your maps in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> provided the functions you're lifting can be equipped with the forgotten structure from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span> safely, which is what it means to be a faithful forgetful functor because of <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/stuff,+structure,+property\">[[stuff, structure, property]]</a></p>\n<p>I think that makes sense</p>",
        "id": 537012375,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1756678861
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Can I even save my earlier confused <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> statement?</p>\n<p>The category of complete ordered fields has one object up to unique isomorphism, which I'll label <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span>, and therefore one homset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>COF</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{COF}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">COF</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> with just the identity.</p>\n<p>A faithful functor from this into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> is given by an injective function from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>COF</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{COF}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">COF</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Then the usual forgetful functor from topological spaces into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> has an injection from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span></span></span></span> in each of these cases are what the \"point\" of the category of complete ordered fields maps to under the forgetful functors into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Top</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Top</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>So in this way, we get nested injections ending in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}(\\mathcal{R}, \\mathcal{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> which is the same as a diagram of subsets.</p>\n<p>So I think we do have a meaningful relationship between these forgetful functors and the illustration of subsets I shared at the beginning of this thread.</p>",
